						               													<description>Way back during the depths of the Great Depression in 1934, patriotic American and underemployed heater salesman Charles B. Darrow literally took an idea he&amp;rsquo;d refined to Parker Brothers, who literally bought it.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;That idea was the board game Monopoly, and Darrow &amp;ndash; who&amp;rsquo;d claimed he&amp;rsquo;d invented it himself &amp;ndash; became the world&amp;rsquo;s first millionaire game designer/capitalist.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;But he didn&amp;rsquo;t invent it &amp;ndash; he only expanded upon versions of traditional games that had been played for generations. In other words, he made it slightly better.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Way back during the aftermath of the Great Recession in 2016, the founders of Diogenes Games &amp;ndash; also underemployed, patriotic Americans and potential millionaire game designers/capitalists  &amp;ndash; literally took an idea born during the historically weird presidential campaign and literally sold it. To you. That idea was the expansion of Darrow&amp;rsquo;s board game Monopoly, called SOCIALISM.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;OBJECT&amp;#10;The object of the game is to achieve total fairness and equality through the renting and selling of property under a modern, progressive, and populist public policy. The game is over when no one is bankrupt and everyone has $300 or less!&amp;#10;&amp;#10;NOTE&amp;#10;The Game consists of an enlightened rule-book, a quick-reference card, 20 &amp;ldquo;Fat Chance&amp;rdquo; and 20 &amp;ldquo;Communism Chest&amp;rdquo; cards, and 4 new game tokens. The object of SOCIALISM: The Game is not to &amp;quot;win,&amp;quot; but instead, is to achieve total fairness and equality through the renting and selling of property under a modern, progressive, and populist public policy.&amp;#10;Requires a copy of Hasbro&amp;rsquo;s MONOPOLY to play.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
